The dystopian sci-fi spectacle Gemini Man boasts an interesting premise - Will Smith confronts his younger version in the film. According to critics, however, the story is the weakest part of the film. The film will be released in Czech cinemas on 10 October.
Henry Brogan (Will Smith) is at the top of his profession. He kills efficiently and without unnecessary questions. One day, however, he decides to hang up his career. Understandably, his employers do not like this and send another killer after Henry. The catch is that the killer is Henry himself, or more precisely, his younger clone created from DNA. Can one determined person win the battle over himself? This time literally.
Three-time Oscar winner Ang Lee was supposed to be a guarantee of quality. Although this is his first sci-fi, he has a wealth of experience with dramatic action films, as he demonstrated, for example, in the above-mentioned Tiger and the Dragon or the western Ride with the Devil. Six screenwriters worked on the script. The most famous is certainly David Benioff, one of the creators of the highly successful Game of Thrones. According to the first reviews, however, even all this was not enough for a good film.
"Even if Ang Lee is trying to do great things in technical filmmaking, the film itself doesn't have enough character to make it stand out," thinks Fionnuala Hannigan from Screen Daily.
The Hollywood Reporter's Stephen Dalton summed up his opinion: "This disappointing film is less than the sum of all the talents involved, with a weak script and plot held together only by the filmmakers' technological wizardry."
"Gemini Man is a case in which a huge amount of work resulted in an incredibly dull action film," Variety reviewer Peter Deburge does not hide his disappointment.
"A muddled product born of a bizarre idea," is how IndieWire's Ella Kemp summed up the film in her review.
"It's hard to care about one man being another man's doppelganger when neither acts human," wrote Nicholas Barber of The Wrap.
