An unusually open and unique portrayal of Karel Gott in Olga Špátová's feature documentary
This unique film by Olga Špátová will premiere in Czech cinemas in the spring of next year.
"In the middle of September last year, Ivanka and Karel Gott called me and asked me if I would like to make a documentary about his life with Karel again after ten years. I did not hesitate for a minute! It was and is a great honour for me to film with a man who has remained in the limelight of Czech culture for more than half a century thanks to his exceptional singing talent, artistic humility and immeasurable hard work. I accepted the challenge to make a feature-length documentary film about Karel Gott, who has brought joy to three generations of listeners with his art, as a commitment to this legendary singer," director Olga Špátová describes her feelings.
Thanks to a quick arrangement and agreement, the first day of shooting took place on 22 October last year and the last shots with Karel Gott were shot a few days ago. The goal was and is absolutely clear - to authentically capture Karel Gott as a phenomenal singer who gives himself to his fans, as a painter, but at the same time a loving husband and father of his children. A man who has been giving joy to several generations with his songs for sixty years, not only in our country, but also in Europe, and actually all over the world. A man who has written himself into the hearts and souls of his listeners by simply being.
The film is not meant to be a showcase of the indisputable fame of Karel Gott and his achievements. "That's why it's not even possible to compare my previous film, The Gott Phenomenon, with this current one. Everyone is different. At least by the fact that we filmed them in a different stage of Karel Gott's life, and this is very evident in his personal, almost intimate confession, which he gave us and which confirmed for all of us what a legend we have the opportunity to work with and spend time with, which is truly indescribable," adds Olga Špátová.
The filmmakers captured Karel Gott at his performances, at meetings with his fans in our country and in Hamburg, but especially in his home environment, whether in Prague, in a cottage in Bohemian Switzerland, in the village where he spent his childhood, and in other places that played an important role in his life. Thanks to Karel Gott's sincere openness, the film will be completely authentic and unique.
"Olga has a great gift for filming with her close team, so that we often let ourselves be carried away by the spontaneous atmosphere and naturally let her into our privacy, thanks to which I talked about quite intimate topics. With her husband, cameraman Jan Malíř, they actually became part of our family. Originally, we wanted to release the film in 2019, when I celebrated my life anniversary. But because I still had a beautiful summer with my family, I wanted us to shoot for as long as possible. Well, and because there was a lot of me everywhere in 2019, my wish was that it would be released in cinemas in the spring of next year. This documentary film is a thank you to my supporters and everyone who supported and accompanied me in my profession," says Karel Gott himself about the film.
