We don't have reliable reproduction, but we don't need to scare people.
Some words have ominous connotations, even though they only convey the state of affairs. One of them is the word "one-child." It refers to a child growing up without siblings, but it does not sound neutral. "You know, an only child," is said, without anything needing to be added. It is interesting that "one-child" has carried this trait since time immemorial, from the days when terms such as demographic crisis were not widely used.
Today, even people outside the scientific community know that a fertility rate of 2.1 children per woman is necessary to ensure the simple reproduction of the population. It is also widely known that no state in Europe today reaches this value. At most, France or Sweden are close to it, but the simple reproduction rate of the population is not guaranteed by European states. (In the West, only Israel with a total fertility of 3.1 children per woman is out of the question.) It is a situation made for alarmism. Therefore, it is not surprising that the Minister of Labour and Social Affairs Maláčová falls for it: "There are almost as many one-child families as two-child families," she said in an interview with LN. However, she omitted the devil hidden in the detail.
Yes, it is good to draw attention to the problem, rather than downplaying or ideologizing it, as in Germany, where the campaign for more children is easily labeled as fascism (in the style of "even Hitler supported it"), it is good to recall that many couples directly plan to have only one child, and it is good if politicians show the will to remove the obstacles that lead to these decisions (for example, the weak extension of work from home discourages women from further pregnancies), but despite all this, let us draw attention to one thing.
When Minister Maláčová says that "there are almost as many one-child families," there is a bit of demagogy in it. That statement was appropriate twenty years ago. Let's recall that fertility in the Czech Republic last ensured simple reproduction in 1980 ("Husák's children"). Then it fell to a terrible 1.14 in 2000. But since then it has risen by almost fifty percent, to the current 1.70 children per woman, which is above the European average. It is still not enough for simple reproduction, so the activity of politicians is appropriate. They can only reduce the alarmism a little.
