Prague Stock Exchange grew slightly, Czech banks, O2 and Avast did well
The Prague Stock Exchange closed the trading week with moderate growth. The PX index rose by 0.13 percent to 1,038.45 points. It was driven upwards by Czech banks, the telecommunications company O2 and the technology company Avast. On the other hand, Austrian titles and the media company CME did not do well. This follows from the results of trading on the stock exchange's website.
For most of Friday's session, the Prague Stock Exchange traded in slightly positive territory and eventually finished with a small profit. "Nevertheless, for the whole week, it (the PX index) lost slightly more than one percent," said Josef Dudek from Fio banka.
Domestic banks partially corrected the declines of the past few days. Komerční banka improved by 0.82 percent to 803 crowns and Moneta Money Bank by 0.41 percent to 72.80 crowns. Avast shares appreciated by 0.89 percent to 113 crowns and the operator O2 gained 0.46 percent to 216.50 crowns.
Kofola's securities grew the most, by 1.38 percent to 294 crowns. The tobacco company Philip Morris gained just under one percent, with its shares rising to 13,640 crowns.
The securities of the energy company ČEZ stagnated at Thursday's value of 520 crowns.
Three titles were loss-making - Erste Bank wrote off 0.87 percent to 779.20 crowns, CME 0.73 percent to 109 crowns and the insurance company VIG 0.40 percent to 618 crowns.
The crown weakened slightly against both major world currencies, losing four pennies to the euro to 25.85 CZK/EUR and three pennies to the dollar to 23.62 CZK/USD, according to data on the Patria Online server.
