A vote in the upper house of the Canadian parliament confirmed a rumor that has been circulating for several days: Canada is revoking the honorary citizenship of the former legend of the fight for human rights, Nobel Peace Prize winner Aung San Suu Kyi. The current leader of Myanmar (Burma), who spent years under house arrest for her efforts to bring freedom to her country, lost her honorary title because of her participation in the genocide against the Rohingya minority.
The decision to strip Suu Kyi of honorary citizenship was approved by the lower legislative body a week ago, and senators have now unanimously supported it. "This is the right message for her, for Myanmar and for the whole world," independent senator Ratna Omidvar commented on the decision of her colleagues. "We must make it clear that accomplices to genocide are not welcome here in Canada - especially as honest citizens."
The verdict of the Canadian parliament does not technically change anything for Suu Kyi, it is only an honorary title, but on a symbolic level it is a strong message for her. The silence of the long-time human rights campaigner to the atrocities that the army of Buddhist-majority Myanmar has been committing for endless months against the Muslim Rohingya minority is unbearable.
The fact that an officially organized genocide is taking place in Myanmar and that Suu Kyi - the de facto prime minister of the government there - has completely failed in her duty to protect her citizens was recently reported by the United Nations. In particular, it mentions the names of several army commanders who, according to the investigation team, should stand trial for crimes against humanity committed in actions that, as the report says, "shock both the horror of their actions and the enormous scale." Suu Kyi and her administration, according to the UN, committed complicity primarily by covering up the actions of the soldiers and releasing a protective fog of lies around them - for example, that it was an "anti-terrorist operation."
With Suu Kyi's removal, five figures remain on Canada's list of honorary citizens: Swedish diplomat Raoul Wallenberg, Nelson Mandela, Tenzin Gyatso, the 14th Dalai Lama, Karim Aga Khan IV, the 49th imam of Shia Muslims, and Malala Yousafzai.
The Canadian Museum for Human Rights has also reflected on the development surrounding the former icon of the fight for freedom and democracy, adding information about the atrocities against the Rohingya and the parliamentary decision to strip her of her honorary citizenship to Suu Kyi's profile. "We have also dimmed the lighting of her photo on the board depicting the timeline of the fight for human rights, and we are thinking of replacing her face with a portrait of a member of the Rohingya minority," Canadian media quote museum spokesman Rory McLeod.
The only thing that will remain of Suu Kyi in the current turmoil - at least for now - is the Nobel Peace Prize, awarded to her at the suggestion of Václav Havel in 1991 for her enormous contribution to the fight for democracy. "Even though Ms Suu Kyi's current actions are regrettable, her award will not be annulled," the head of the Nobel Foundation, Lars Heikensten, told the Canadian CBS.
