The Attorney General has resumed the prosecution of a mother who manipulated her daughter against her father
The Supreme Public Prosecutor, Pavel Zeman, does not agree with the acquittal of the mother, who has been manipulating her daughter for a long time and disturbing her relationship with her father. She was facing charges of abuse and endangering her upbringing. The Regional Court acquitted her of the charges, but Zeman does not agree with this. According to his appeal to the Supreme Court, similar behaviour can be seen as a criminal offence.
The Supreme Court's decision could have a broader impact on other cases. "A more specific definition of such a specific form of abuse can be considered necessary from the point of view of regulating further application practice," reads Zeman's appeal.
Last year, the district court in Svitavy initially found the woman guilty of mistreating a person entrusted to her and endangering the upbringing of a child. She created a strong, almost symbiotic bond with her daughter, even in a situation where she was to be entrusted to her father.
The result was a pathological fixation on the mother and a markedly negative relationship with the father. The situation affected the emotional development of the daughter, who was even hospitalized because she threatened to self-harm if she was placed in the father's care.
The Svitavy court sentenced the mother to two years in prison with a two-year suspended sentence. However, the Pardubice branch of the regional court acquitted the woman on appeal, saying it was not a criminal offence. The regional court repeated the same verdict even after the Supreme Court had already ordered it to decide again.
The regional court stated that situations where one of the parents manipulates the child towards the other are by no means exceptional. They are dealt with in custody proceedings, possibly with the help of psychologists or youth welfare authorities. Only in exceptional cases is criminal law the solution.
According to the Supreme Public Prosecutor, however, the woman committed both abuse and endangerment of education. "The accused acted quite purposefully when she aroused negative feelings towards her father in her daughter and purposefully reinforced these negative emotions. By doing so, she not only pursued the unlawful intention to restrict or exclude the father's contact with the minor, but she must have been aware that she would cause negative consequences in the psychosocial sphere of the minor," the appeal states.
Zeman asked the Supreme Court to return the case once again to the regional court. The appeal implies that the child is now in the care of the father.
