The repair of the Krkonoše Museum will be a year late
The administration of the Krkonoše National Park (KRNAP) has postponed the deadline for submitting bids for the second tender for the repair of the Krkonoše Museum in Vrchlabí by three weeks. The original deadline for opening the envelopes was 20 September, said the spokesman for the National Park, Radek Drahný. The reason for the postponement of the deadline for submitting bids is the reduction of the budget from 110 million crowns to 83 million crowns.
"We are currently working with the prices that are on the market. There has been a change in the budget, this is the price that we expect to be offered. If someone makes an offer that is acceptable, then the work will begin as soon as possible," said Drahný.
As opposed to the original plans, the start of the repair of the museum is about a year late. KRNAP wanted to have the selected supplier of the construction part by the end of last year and to begin construction work this spring. According to the management of the national park administration, the European subsidies of 123 million crowns for the project are not at risk.
The KRNAP administration has not been able to select a construction company for the repairs of the museum. A second tender was announced this summer, because in the previous tender, all bids from companies significantly exceeded the then expected price of 65 million. Bids exceeded 100 million crowns.
The museum, which is housed in a former Augustinian monastery and belongs to the KRNAP Administration, has been closed since the autumn of 2017. The selected company should provide the construction part of the project. The total costs, including the construction of a new exhibition, are estimated at 210 million crowns. The KRNAP visitor centre should be built in the now vacated building by the end of 2021 after the conversion of the exhibitions.
The renovated museum with a new interactive exhibition, which should be a story of nature and people settled in the mountains and build on the successful exhibition Stone and Life, should serve as a representative gateway to the Krkonoše for visitors. The visitor centre should provide information about the past and present of the Krkonoše in the clearest possible form and motivate people to discover the mountains and their protection. It should also take on the role of a traditional museum. The centre will also offer the possibility of organising concerts, festivals, theatre performances or lectures in the open air. The plans include the construction of a new entrance to the building, the creation of a research room or a café.
