In 1992, at the height of the wave of liberalism that followed the end of the Cold War and the fall of the Iron Curtain, the political scientist wrote in his most famous book, The End of History and the Last Man: "What we may be witnessing... is the end point of mankind's ideological evolution and the universal acceptance of Western liberal democracy as the final form of government."
Twenty-six years later, we are witnessing the triumph of illiberal models and various forms of nationalism and radicalism from the United States to Russia, from Turkey to Poland and from Hungary to Italy. Fukuyama's current ninth book, Identity: The Demand for Dignity and the Politics of Resentment, attempts to come to terms with the emergence of these forces. As his interview with George Eaton for the New Statesman shows, he is reconsidering many of his former positions: he claims that the ideas of socialism should return to the public space and that Marx was right in many respects, although he also insists that his development of thought is still in line with the position of the nineties and that the critics of The End of History and the Last Man did not understand correctly.
"What I was saying back then was that one of the problems with modern democracy is that it provides peace and prosperity, but people want more than that... Liberal democracy doesn't even try to define what a good life is. It leaves it to individuals who feel alienated, who don't see the point, and therefore group themselves according to an identity that gives them a sense of belonging."
At the time, The End of History and the Last Man was written as a strong argument against Marxists who saw communism as the final stage of history. When asked how he now sees the rise of socialists in Britain and the US, Fukuyama replies: "It all depends on what you mean by socialism. If we are talking about the ownership of the means of production, then, except when there is a demand for clear services to the public, I don't think it will work. But if you mean redistributive programs that try to solve the huge imbalances in income and wealth that we are witnessing, then yes. I think not only could it come back, it should come back. The long period that started with President Reagan and Prime Minister Thatcher, in which certain types of ideas about the advantages of an unregulated market came into play, had a disastrous effect in many respects."
Finally, Fukuyama tries to calm down the current situation and warns all liberals that even the emergence of new, not entirely democratic regimes will not mean the end of history.
