Due to the restructuring, Kovosvit ended last year with a consolidated loss of 100 million crowns, with a consolidated turnover of 1.3 billion. Kuchař ranks the lack of workers and shifts of subcontractors among last year's main problems. This year, the demand for machine tools fell by 10 to 20 percent year-on-year. "This is also related to the expected decline in turnover by about ten percent," said the CEO. In 2017, Kovosvit had sales of 1.3 billion crowns and a profit after tax of 40.1 million. The loss for 2016 was 719 million.
Kovosvit is now offering for sale several properties, halls and plots of land, which it either does not use or only minimally. This also applies to the administrative building, where it uses two of the five floors, and not yet completely. "Part of the long-term restructuring plan is to slim down Kovosvit, to make its activities more efficient. The sale of assets is not part of a momentary solution, whether it is, for example, cash-flow, but part of a long-term plan, when we want to devote all resources to investment development," said the CEO.
Kovosvit exports roughly half of its production. Its standard markets are the EU and Russia, last year to a lesser extent Asia. This year, Kuchař ranks India among the most interesting, where Kovosvit won an order for machines enabling five-axis machining worth 100 million crowns. This year, the company also exported two five-axis machines worth 30 million crowns to China. "Another order of the same volume is being negotiated, which we would like to fulfil before the end of the year," said Kuchař. On the Russian market and elsewhere, Kovosvit is facing restrictions due to sanctions.
Last year, the company sold two five-axis machining centers to France, a company that is a subcontractor of Airbus. This May, it delivered another machine, and it is expected to deliver another one at the end of the year or at the beginning of 2020.
The company's main investment this year was the switch from steam to hot water heating for 20 million crowns. Kovosvit employs 500 people, the average worker's wage is 28,500 crowns. The company is looking for grinders of castings for the foundry, machinists, lathe operators and electricians.
The company has been owned by industrialist and arms manufacturer Jaroslav Strnad since September 2016. The company has a tradition in the production of machine tools. It was founded in 1939 by Tomáš Baťa. At one time, the company had up to three thousand employees.
