Everyone knows what is going on. And anyone who occasionally travels through the Czech Republic sees a number of the devastated monuments - from the centres of historic towns to individual castles, monasteries, old houses, churches or farms - with their own eyes. Everyone suspects that demagogy may also come into play here. If we accuse the town hall of not caring about monuments or some horror in the land-use plan, it may be the work of former administrations. Or a privatised object whose owner is not traceable. The head of state calls on local politicians: "Paragraph of the Heritage Act allows you to fine the owners of objects who do not take care of their property." But even if the owner is not traceable, it must be admitted that the president calls for the enforcement of the law. Which even critics of his bending of the constitution should recognise as a plus.
Of course, Miloš Zeman would not be Miloš Zeman if he considered all the details and formalities of a complex problem. But he is standing up for a good cause, just like the squatters, whom he himself does not recognise. Two years ago, we wrote: "Despite all the abuse, the squatters are drawing attention to a problem that is not of current interest. To the fact that this or that building is in a state of disrepair." And let's admit that the president is de facto doing the same thing.
