There are up to sixty times fewer insects than 40 years ago
No other animal group is more present in nature than insects. Beetles, butterflies and other species make up more than half of life on Earth. But there are increasing reports that the insect kingdom is radically shrinking. Another scientific study on this topic was published just this week, and the situation is even more serious than mankind has hitherto realized.
The study is based on field research in the tropical forest of Puerto Rico, in which American scientists copied a similar survey from 1976. As they write right at the beginning of the report, there are "ten to sixty times fewer insects" in the forest today. This is a decline in the entire population, not the number of species, and the research concerned not only insects, but all arthropods. Due to the extinction of insects, the population of other fauna, which is dependent on insects in the food chain, such as birds, frogs or lizards, is also shrinking.
The authors of the research put their conclusions in direct connection with climate change. According to them, the average air temperature in the forest has risen by two degrees Celsius over the past thirty years and warming has become the driving force behind the collapse of the food chain. According to the authors, the study shows that the impact of climate change on tropical ecosystems may be much greater than previously assumed.
The report was the subject of a major article in the Washington Post on Monday, which described the new findings as hyper-alarming in its headline. "It's one of the most disturbing articles I've ever read," entomologist David Wagner from the University of Connecticut, whom the paper quotes as an independent expert, told the paper.
The extinction of insects also concerns Europe. "In our country, the decline is also of an order of magnitude," points out Lukas Cizek from the Entomological Institute of the Academy of Sciences. According to him, in addition to climate change, it is also necessary to take into account changes in the landscape, which play a significant role in Europe. "In our country, it just takes a much longer time than in Puerto Rico," adds Cizek to explain why scientists were able to measure such a rapid decline in the forest compared to the 1970s.
Nokia is suing a Brno company over the name Lokia. People will not mistake us, Moravians believe
Nokia has objected to the application of the Lokia brand to the Industrial Property Office. However, according to the CCV, product substitution is not likely.
The Brno-based company developing the CCV software is facing legal action from the Finnish telecommunications equipment manufacturer Nokia. The Finns do not like the fact that the Brno-based company's warehouse management program is called Lokia WMS, wrote the E15 daily. Nokia has therefore filed objections against the application for the Lokia trademark with the Industrial Property Office. CCV believes that confusion is not likely.
Marketing Director Petr Ondrášek said that two dozen customers are already using the program, which has been on the market since last September.
"The Nokia brand is recognized and trusted around the world, and when someone attempts to register a mark that we believe may cause confusion or dilute our brand, we take action to protect our valuable asset," said Nokia spokesman Mark Durrant.
The Brno developers claim that they did not think about the brand, famous in the past for mobile phones, when creating the warehouse program. The designation Lokia according to CCV is based on the Latin name for a type of dragonfly, whose rapid movement is supposed to be an analogy of the movement of warehouse workers around the warehouse.
"On the Czech market, the possibility of confusion is unlikely. We sell modern cloud software, which companies use to equip their warehouse operations, and we are not really heading into the production of mobile phones. And we do not want to be compared to a brand that may be losing its way in its industry," said CCV manager Tomáš Kormaňák in E15.
CCV applied for trademark protection with the Industrial Property Office in August, before the programme was launched on the market. "It applied for protection for products and services belonging to classes 9, 35 and 42, since the software belongs to class 9, the related services of managing business activities in the warehouse belong to class 35 and the development of computer software to class 42 according to the international classification," said Ondrášek.
Nokia's objection is based on the fact that the earlier Nokia trademark is valid in all classes of goods and services, and thus applies to the widest possible range of goods and services, and therefore, of course, also overlaps in classes 9, 35 and 42. "CCV does not dispute the claimant's assertion as far as it concerns the conformity of these classes of goods and services. However, in reality, they are completely different brands aimed at different target groups," said Ondrášek.
According to E15, the dispute over the brand may last for months and it may complicate the company's activities.
