Developer Dušan Kunovský and architect Josef Pleskot, in a television interview on the occasion of the Summit of Architecture and Development, however, also cited other, far less "rosy" data. For example, the Czech Republic is 154th in the world in the speed of construction proceedings. It may happen that the current economic "boom" will not leave behind any significant building heritage as it was in the past.
The biggest obstacle is not only the existing legislation, but also the slow, inefficient bureaucracy, which is also documented by comparative studies, in which the Czech Republic lags significantly behind developed countries in the overall quality and performance of public administration.
Our country has simply not yet been able to make good use of the potential of the good economic situation of recent years to invest in the future. Although it is nice that salaries and pensions are increasing, people with a better standard of living will also want to have a place to live, to travel in a modern and fast way, to have quality cultural stands, to live without an unbearable environmental burden.
But in the capital city of Prague, for example, it has not been possible for years to complete the inner and outer ring road or to build a high-speed railway or a metro to the airport. And Prague does not even have a modern, architecturally daring national library, concert hall or national gallery. The reason for this is not only the absurd scramble for architectural competitions, zoning plans and building permits, but also a specifically Czech conservatism, which adheres to the motto "every bold change is for the worse."
