Declaration of the End of the Right in the Chamber of Deputies, or What Kind of "Right-Wing" Coalition of ODS, TOP 09, STAN, and KDU?
The media and commentators have recently been reporting on the planned coalition of the parties mentioned. Many are applauding the fact that the "right" is finally getting its act together, but I'm more inclined to ask why these parties are still calling themselves right-wing.
If I ignore the new Trikolora movement, the Czech Chamber of Deputies no longer has a real right-wing party. And it makes no difference how the subjects label themselves or what label the mainstream media parrot. ODS is hardly centrist in its average of top politicians of this party, TOP 09 is clearly a party of the urban pseudo-liberal left (which is ashamed of its left-wingness and thus hypocritically describes itself as conservative or even right-wing). STAN is a party that basically merges with TOP 09 in its concept, ideology and voter targeting (the reason for its existence is simply not clear to me). And KDU has even been labeling itself as centrist for a long time - but their political compass is much more to the left than they say.
Do you have the feeling that I have taken everyone out of the same water? No, I am basing myself on the real political steps of these parties. If I consider myself a classically liberal right-wing voter, the highest value for me is the freedom of the individual, the free market and minimal state interference in the lives of individuals and the economy. How do these parties fulfil this general assumption of right-wingness? How many laws cutting people's freedoms by the salami method, increasing taxes, confirming new regulations and increasing supervision, increasing ties to the socialist EU or supporting environmental and gender madness have they supported in recent years? A lot, really a lot. Not their own labels, but actions identify them. These parties, despite all kinds of declarations or partial concessions, want to strengthen the role of the state in our lives. And this has nothing to do with right-wingness.
I would not be at all surprised by the coalition cooperation of TOP 09, STAN and KDU, they simply belong together on the political map and, with the exception of Christian or, on the contrary, homosexual and gender aspects, I basically do not see any obvious difference for voters in terms of the influence of the state on their lives. Nevertheless, ODS has long portrayed itself as "the only right-wing party" and, by linking with these three entities, it is already openly revealing its true political affiliation.
By the way, when I briefly mentioned the labels, have you noticed how often all these parties quite consistently and cheaply label the critics of dirigisme and socialism coming from the European Union as pro-Russian agents? Are they unable or just unwilling to understand that there are many people for whom Eurosocialism and the growing lack of freedom do not smell as strongly as the authoritarian regime in Russia? Are they not concealing their utter inability to argue and their groundless or blind adoration of the conditions in the European Union?
In short, it is possible that in the Czech Republic only centrist politics has a chance of greater success. Maybe voters really want this kind of combination. Maybe they want left-centrist politics under the guise of "right-wing," because they are ashamed of their political convictions (or they can't even identify them). I don't know. But I am definitely not one of those voters.
