Přindiš, Prskavec and Fišerová safely advanced to the semi-finals of the World Championship
Kayakers Vít Přindiš and Jiří Prskavec and canoeist Tereza Fišerová safely advanced to the semi-finals of the World Championships in Water Slalom in Seu d'Urgell. Přindiš was fourth in Friday's qualification, Prskavec fifth and Fišerová eighth. The other three Czech representatives will be in Spain to strive for a semi-final start in the afternoon qualifying race.
Vavřinec Hradilek did not succeed from the strong representative group of kayakers, who received a fifty-second penalty for incorrectly passing the goal at the very beginning of the ride. Přindiš and Prskavec, on the other hand, can now rest and concentrate on Sunday's semi-final.
"I set myself the goal of finishing in the top 30 in the first run, which I managed to do. Not that I didn't care how I did, because the start on Sunday is very early in the morning, so I was hoping to be a little higher to have a better starting position," said Přindiš, praising his well-being in Seu. "Before the patrol race I felt the worst in the 14 days we've been here. Then during the race it was good and today it was better again. It's been beautiful here the whole time, nice races, spectators came, so it's fine," he smiled.
Prskavec was also satisfied. "In qualifying, you don't want to make an unnecessary mistake. I wasn't completely successful in the first goals. Then I drove the middle perfectly, without any problems, and I knew that I had enough mileage, so the second mistake came when I wanted to go straight down and I turned the knob. Overall, I can't be dissatisfied. The form is there, we'll see how it goes," said this year's overall World Cup winner.
Both representatives praised themselves for not going to the start on Sunday until the end of the semi-final block. "I'm not a morning person, it's cold here in the morning, and when you're here at eight o'clock, you need a jacket and a sweatshirt," said Přindiš. "Overall, the semi-final takes an hour and a half, which is quite a good difference in terms of sleep," agreed Prskavec.
Fišerová was the only one of the three Czech canoeists to succeed, Eva Říhová finished two places behind the top twenty, while Kateřina Havlíčková was 35th. "I skied the upper part as planned, in the middle section I felt like I wasn't keeping up and wasn't going as planned, but I managed to get into the comfortable lane I wanted to go. I made two nudges and I'm just behind the winner with a clear time. I have a good starting position for the semi-finals," Fišerová praised herself.
Hunter injured in fall from perch, carried to ambulance for three hours
The unfortunate accident occurred before half past seven in the evening during the top matches at Čertův mlýn.
"It was a very difficult and inaccessible terrain, so we sent five of our rescuers with the appropriate equipment to the injured man. At the same time, we requested the cooperation of the Medical Rescue Service of the Moravian-Silesian Region. The medics then sent an ambulance to the accident," Libor Kluz, dispatcher of the Beskydy Mountain Rescue Service, described the circumstances of the intervention.
The rescuers found the hunter in the selected location with multiple injuries. They immediately treated him and then gently, but with difficulty, transported him on a so-called Austrian wheelchair across the impassable terrain.
