Bloomberg: Venezuela has hidden bitcoins and doesn't know what to do with them
Venezuela's central bank is carrying out internal tests to see if it can hold cryptocurrencies, in response to a request from state-run Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which wants to be able to send bitcoins and ethers to the central bank and then have the bank pay the oil company's suppliers in cryptocurrencies. Employees are also studying a proposal to allow the central bank to count cryptocurrencies in foreign reserves, which are now near a 30-year low, Bloomberg reported, citing four sources.
Sanctions imposed by the United States on the authoritarian regime of President Nicolas Maduro have largely cut Venezuela off from the global financial system, further deepening the country's economic crisis - one of the most severe in the world - and forcing officials to use a patchwork of different ways to move money. While Maduro's attempt to launch the world's first state cryptocurrency has failed, the continued push to use digital currencies shows how desperate the government is to find ways around the restrictions.
Neither the Central Bank of Venezuela nor PDVSA responded to requests for comment.
It is not clear how PDVSA came to own bitcoins and ethers, nor how much value of these currencies it owns. The company has problems obtaining payments from customers through conventional channels, because large banks are not willing to do business with entities that are subject to sanctions. Last month, the company received most of the payment of 700 million dollars (16.6 billion CZK) in Chinese yuan, because the parties were unable to find financial institutions that would allow the transaction.
PDVSA may not want to sell cryptocurrencies on the open market, as this would require it to be listed on the stock exchange and subject to due diligence. Instead, it wants the cryptocurrency to be used by the central bank to pay the entities to which PDVSA owes. The oil company's representatives believe that the central bank is less exposed to any obstacles that may arise when paying with cryptocurrencies.
Bitcoins and ethers use a decentralized online ledger known as a blockchain to verify and record transactions, in some cases allowing for relatively anonymous transfers without the need for a middleman. Few banks are involved in digital currencies because of money laundering and client information issues that come with them and complicate compliance.
After the debacle in 2018, cryptocurrencies are experiencing a return to the limelight this year thanks to expectations of their greater acceptance by institutions and Facebook's plan to come up with its own cryptocurrency. Even so, they remain unstable. Bitcoin has fallen by almost 20 percent over the past four days, but since the beginning of the year it has gained about 130 percent.
