Annex No. 6 / Methodology of project management
1. Charter of the project
1.1 The purpose of the Project Charter is to define the formal management processes and the method of communication between the parties for the purpose of fulfilling the subject of the Contract so that the implementation of the work or the provision of services is in accordance with the Contract and this Project Management Methodology. The Project Charter makes available to the persons involved in the implementation of the work or the provision of services those parts of the Contract that are necessary to fulfill its subject. The Project Charter determines the staffing of the organizational structure of the project, the method of communication, the control and escalation mechanisms and the structure of the project portal, on which all documentation related to the implementation of the work or the provision of services is archived. The project charter is prepared by the project managers and approved by the initial meeting of the Steering committee.
2. Organizational structure of the project
2.1 The organizational components of the Project are (1) Project Steering Committee (hereinafter referred to as "SCP") and (2) Project Management Team (hereinafter referred to as "PMT") and (3) Work Teams. SCP and PMT are permanent organizational components of the Project. Work Teams are temporary organizational components of the Project.
3. Steering committee
3.1 The powers of the SCP / Steering Committee of the project are in particular:
3.1.1 approves the Charter of the project; and
3.1.2. resolve the escalated issues that have not been resolved at the PVP level; and
3.1.3. address issues affecting the scope of work performed or services provided; and
3.1.4. resolve issues related to the delivery schedule; and
3.1.5. resolve issues related to remuneration or the structure of remuneration for services provided or work performed; and
3.1.6. accepts individual deliveries, services, parts of the work or the work as a whole; and
3.2 Members of the SCP / On behalf of the Client, the members of the SCP are (1) the project sponsor for business and (2) the director of the ISIT division and (3) the project manager. On behalf of the Contractor, the members of the SCP are (1) the management representative and (2) the project manager.
3.3 Meetings of the SCP / The SCP meets at least once a quarter. The exact days on which the SCP meets on a regular basis are determined by the project manager in the project charter. The SCP meets whenever a significant milestone in the delivery schedule is evaluated (e.g. start or end of the acceptance procedure). The SCP meets whenever a project manager calls for a meeting of the SCP. The SCP meets at the Customer's headquarters.
3.4 The SCP meeting agenda / SCP meeting agenda and the documents to be discussed will be delivered to the SCP members by the project manager on behalf of the Contractor, at least 3 working days before the SCP meeting. At its meeting, the SCP will always discuss the project status report and draft minutes related to the acceptance of the delivery, services or work.
3.5 The right to invite experts and advisers / If a party deems it necessary, it has the right to invite experts or advisers to the SCP meeting, but it will inform the other party in advance and state the reasons why the presence of experts or advisers at the SCP meeting is useful.
3.6 Voting / After each item on the agenda has been discussed, the members of the SCP vote on the motion that has been submitted for the relevant item on the agenda. Each member of the SCP has one vote.
3.7 Decisions of the SCP affecting the contractual conditions / If the decision of the SCP concerns the contractual conditions under which the work is performed or the services are provided, in particular if the decision of the SCP affects the remuneration for which the work is performed or the services are provided, the Client shall prepare an amendment to the contract in question without undue delay after the adoption of such a decision.
3.8 Minutes / The SCP meeting minutes shall be prepared by the project manager on behalf of the Client and delivered to the project manager on behalf of the Contractor.
4. Project management
4.1 The responsibilities of the PVP / Project Management of the project are in particular:
4.1.1. controls all the outputs of the individual phases of the execution of the work or the provision of services; and
4.1.2. evaluate and refine the delivery schedule and the progress of work in the execution of the work or the provision of services; and
4.1.3 discusses amendments that do not affect the wording of the Treaty; and
4.1.4. manage the cooperation between the Client and the Contractor; and
4.1.5. manage the risks and remedies associated with performing the work or providing the services; and
4.1.6 escalates into an SCP meeting.
4.2 Members of the PVP / For the Customer, the members of the PVP are (1) the project manager and (2) the chief business analyst and (3) the application architect. For the Contractor, the members of the PVP are (1) the project manager and (2) the chief analyst and (3) the chief architect.
4.3 SCP/PVP meetings shall be held once a week, at the Customer's registered office or by means of remote communication.
4.4 The agenda of the PVP meeting and documents / The agenda of the PVP meeting and documents to be discussed shall be delivered to the PVP members by the project manager on behalf of the Contractor, at least 1 working day before the PVP meeting. At its meeting, the PVP shall always discuss:
4.4.1 implementation of open tasks from previous PIPs; and
4.4.2 the progress of the execution of the work or the provision of services; and
4.4.3 implementation and updating of the schedule of works; and
4.4.4 the issues identified and how they are being addressed; and
4.4.5 a roadmap; and
4.4.6 risks associated with the execution of the work or the provision of services; and
4.4.7 evaluation and other requirements for the cooperation of the Customer; and
4.4.8 the status and severity of unresolved defects or incidents; and
4.4.9 change requests; and
4.5 The right to invite experts and advisers / If their presence is useful for the effective course of the negotiations, both parties have the right to invite experts and advisers, or members of project teams, to the PVP negotiations.
4.6 Minutes / The project manager will prepare minutes of the PVP meeting on behalf of the Client, which will be delivered to the project manager on behalf of the Contractor.
5. Work teams
5.1 Work teams / work teams consist of employees of the Client or the Contractor and, where applicable, employees of third parties. Work teams, in particular, (1) carry out specific parts of the work or services provided and (2) provide the know-how necessary for the execution of the work or the provision of services and (3) provide factual and expert evidence for further decision-making.
5.2 Roles in work teams / Occupation of roles is always adapted to the current stage of work performance or provision of services. On the part of the Customer, members of the work team are:
5.2.1 Business analysts of subject area (s)
5.2.2 Guarantor / key user of the subject area (s)
5.2.3 Technical and technological infrastructure specialist
On the part of the Contractor, the members of the work team are:
5.2.4 Principal consultant/analyst - architect of the proposed solution
5.2.5 Consultant/analyst
5.2.6 Technical infrastructure specialist
5.2.7 Developer
5.2.8 Testers, trainers
5.2.9 Operation and installation specialist
6. A complete overview of the assignment of individual project roles and their communication matrix is determined by the Project Charter.
6.1 Communication management / Communication in the project is mainly managed by the project manager. Communication is always conducted objectively with the aim of solving individual tasks as quickly and efficiently as possible. Mutual, controlled communication between project teams includes in particular:
6.1.1 Project negotiations (SCP, PVP, consultations, workshops, ...)
6.1.2 Acceptance and transfer procedures
6.1.3 Transmission and storage of tasks, information and documents
6.1.4 Registration of change requests
6.1.5 Records of defects and incidents
6.2 Project meetings - agenda and documents / The plan and list of tasks from project meetings are always updated at the next meeting. The documents that will be the subject of the project meeting will be sent by the project manager to the meeting participants in advance according to the subject of the meeting. The documents are recorded and updated on the project portal.
6.3 Minutes of project meetings / The Client's project manager shall prepare a written record of each project meeting, which shall be delivered to the Contractor's project manager on the working day following the project meeting.
6.4 Editing and supplementing the minutes of the project meeting / Editing and supplementing the minutes of the project meeting will be carried out by the participants within 2 working days from the date of delivery of the minutes. Negotiations on editing and supplementing the minutes are managed by the project manager. Editing and supplementing the minutes is not a place for discussion. After incorporating the edits and supplements, the Client's project manager will close the minutes of the project meeting and save it on the project portal. The deadline for commenting on the minutes of the project meeting can be changed by the project managers by agreement. If any deadline for commenting on the minutes of the project meeting expires without comments from the participants of the meeting, the minutes are considered approved.
7. Risk management
7.1 Identification and recording of risks / During the execution of the work or the provision of services, all persons involved identify and subsequently manage risks in a documented manner that may affect the quality of outputs or deadlines for the execution of the work or the provision of services. Risks are recorded by the project manager on the project portal, including their severity.
7.2 Discussion of risks at the PVP meeting / Discussion and evaluation of risks is a mandatory item on the agenda of each PVP meeting. The PVP meeting determines measures to eliminate or minimize risks.
7.3 Escalation / If there is a disagreement or if a risk is identified with a severity affecting the contractual arrangement or the schedule or remuneration, such risk will be escalated by the PVP to the SCP.
8. Quality management
8.1 The basic tool for managing the quality of project outputs is the acceptance procedure.
8.1.1 Checking the completeness of the subject of the work or the provision of services so that the purpose of the contract is fulfilled
8.1.2 Evaluation and settlement of comments, defects and incidents so that the purpose of the contract is fulfilled
8.1.3 Checking that documentation is up to date and complete
8.1.4 Monitoring compliance with the delivery schedule
8.1.5 Implementation of approved changes
8.1.6 Results of other agreed activities according to the minutes of the meeting.
