Annex No. 7 / Classification of incidents
The items below are for inspiration only. This appendix must be formulated precisely and exhaustively by the project manager.
Incidents from the operational environment
A category A incident means an incident in an operational environment if, for example:
the user cannot log in to the Application
when the Application repeatedly crashes at the same step and the user cannot complete a critical process
when the system is too long (double the defined performance parameters)
responses to user activity
when it is not possible to print the documentation or report for the client
when incorrect data is displayed to the end customer
The critical functions/processes of the application are:
opening or closing an account
start of daily closing
A category B incident means an incident in an operational environment where, for example:
the user's work is slowed down, but it does not seriously affect the compliance of the workflow
when non-critical functionality is not available to the end customer.
A category C incident means an incident in an operational environment where, for example:
in the case of a language defect or a font other than the agreed font
when it is a graphical error in the user interface that does not mislead the user in the use of the interface
when there is a defect in the documentation
Incidents from the acceptance environment
An incident of category TA means an incident in an acceptance environment if, for example:
it is not possible to create a client in the system
A TB incident means an Incident in an Acceptance Environment if, for example:
It is not possible to change the default parameter of the client account
A TC incident means an incident in an acceptance environment if, for example:
in the case of a language defect or a font other than the agreed font
when it is a graphical error in the user interface that does not mislead the user in the use of the interface
when there is a defect in the documentation
