Sabre combines a conventional aircraft engine with a rocket engine. It is designed to propel the aircraft at twice the speed of the Concorde. "When the Sabre engine is put into operation, it could allow us to fly to Australia in about four hours," said Turnock. And for example, the distance between London and New York could be covered by the aircraft in one hour.
The Independent notes that so-called hypersonic flights, which exceed five times the speed of sound, are complicated by engine overheating, but Sabre (Synergetic Air Breathing Rocket Engine) should solve this problem thanks to the use of super-cold helium, which should prevent temperatures from rising.
"The most important thing about Sabre is that it's a hybrid of a rocket engine and an aircraft engine, which is powered by a stream of exhaust gases created from the air," says Shaun Driscoll from Reaction Engines. "Rockets haven't evolved that much in the last 70 years, whereas aircraft engines have. So when you combine the engines, you can have a very light and efficient propulsion system and essentially create a space plane," he added.
