The traditionally high-profile battle for the fastest man on the planet will be a hunt for defending silver medalist Christian Coleman at the world championships. The 23-year-old American is the world leader with a time of 9.81 seconds and has only lost once this year. However, his start at the top of the season was threatened due to a case of missed doping tests.
The United States Anti-Doping Agency (USADA) closed his case at the beginning of September without bringing charges due to formal reasons. Although Coleman did not take three doping tests last year and this year, it was not within 12 months. The World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) dated his first offense back to April 1, 2018, i.e. the beginning of the second quarter, but he did not miss the test itself until June 6. And since the third omission occurred on April 29, 2019, Coleman did not commit the offense of three unperformed controls within 12 months.
"I don't take drugs, I don't take anything legal. A lot of athletes take legal creatine or protein powder or various other supplements for faster recovery. And I don't take anything, I work hard and that's it," he said before the start of the World Championships.
He suffered his only defeat from six starts in the 100m this year right at the start of the season at the Diamond League in Shanghai, where he was beaten by just six thousandths of a second by compatriot Noah Lyles. He took advantage of Coleman's absence to triumph in the Diamond League final, but he will only run the 200m at the World Championships.
On paper, the second fastest competitor is 22-year-old Nigerian Divine Oduduru with a performance of 9.86, but he has only done well at American university competitions.
The title will be defended by the thirty-seven-year-old American Justin Gatlin, who shone with a time of 9.87 at Stanford in June. However, he only ran the last hundred in Zagreb in 10.29 because he slightly injured his hamstring.
South African Akani Simbine, three-time Rio Olympic medallist Andre de Grasse and European champion Zharnel Hughes are also among the favourites. The fastest Jamaican is 2011 world champion Yohan Blake with a time of 9.96.
The men's hundred starts on Friday with the preliminary round and heats. The semi-finals and finals are scheduled for Saturday. The medals will be run at 21:15 CEST.
