Epilepsy complicated his love of sports, thanks to the operation he has new hope
Honzík's parents first noticed that something was wrong with him when he was a year and a half old. He always stared into space for several minutes, became motionless and did not respond to anyone. The paediatrician therefore sent him to a paediatric neurology clinic, where, after a series of examinations, the doctors diagnosed him with epilepsy and immediately put him on medication, which did not work immediately.
It took almost a year for the doctors to find the ideal combination of drugs, thanks to which he completely stopped having seizures. At the age of five, the doctors stopped the medication, and since the seizures did not return, the parents thought that Honza was healthy and began to encourage him to do more sports. He rode a bike, skied, played tennis and floorball, and spent his free time playing with his sister and friends. However, at the age of eleven, he had another seizure and everything started all over again.
Doctors again tried various combinations of medications, but this time nothing worked, seizures in the form of absences kept recurring. Since Honza always lost consciousness during a seizure, his parents were terrified that he would get it during sports and get injured. Gradually, Honza stopped cycling and replaced his downhill skis with cross-country skis and a snowboard. Although the sport caused him to have a seizure from time to time, he never completely gave it up. He even fulfilled his dream and finished the Spartan Race, but together with a friend who kept an eye on him to help in case of emergency.
When Honza was 15 years old, his parents decided to try a different doctor and turned to specialists at the University Hospital in Motol. After a series of examinations, the doctors there concluded that Honza was a candidate for a surgical procedure to remove a lesion from his brain - the source of epileptic seizures. "I had to undergo two operations in a row. First, the doctors inserted probes into my brain to measure its activity, and only then could they remove the lesion. It was hell for me for several weeks. I had to just lie there and barely move, with wires sticking out of my head that were connected to a computer," recalls Honza.
The operation was successful and the doctors removed the relatively large lesion. "The first days after the operation were very mentally demanding, Honza was apathetic, confused, sad and hardly spoke. Compared to how he is normally lively and communicative, it was a frightening change, but fortunately everything returned to normal after a few days," says his mother and adds: "A month and a half after the operation he had one seizure, but according to the doctors this happens. Since then he has been seizure-free for 3 months."
This school year, Honza will be graduating from high school. In addition to sports, he enjoys languages and has begun to work with Company E, with which he visits schools for discussions on epilepsy. Honza is not yet fully engaged in sports activities, he is slowly returning to sports. "I am learning how to play sports properly, how to breathe well, so that I do not expose my body to sudden stress, which is quite a challenge with my competitive nature," explains Honza.
This year, therefore, he will not yet actively participate in the traditional EPPI canoe triathlon, which brings together epileptic patients and healthy athletes and which takes place this weekend on 28 September 2019 at the Veselská sand pit. But perhaps next year.
