At first glance, there is nothing complicated about it.
Most nouns in Czech express only one grammatical gender, and it is therefore not a problem to determine whether they are masculine, feminine or neuter.
But then there is also a relatively large group of nouns for which the gender is not stable.
Such nouns fluctuate between two genders.
When folded, they acquire double endings and in some cases remain in an unbent form.
For example, the words "svízel" or "kyčel" are masculine and feminine, in the former they are inflected according to the pattern "machine," in the latter according to the pattern "song."
In the next group of nouns, there are different forms in the first case of the singular, for example: "row/row," "kedluben/kedlubna" or "brambor/brambora" (meaning food).
Both forms are grammatical, have the same meaning, and are therefore freely interchangeable.
Some expressions may differ regionally, for example "okurka" in Bohemia and "okurek" in Moravia, but in this case the Moravian variant is not written, similarly, there are other Czech-Moravian pairs of words: "moat" and "moat," "doughnut" and "doughnut," etc.
Some words that entered the Czech language from other languages were originally oblique, but they are gradually adopting Czech endings.
A typical example is the expression "image," which is both masculine and feminine, or the word "buffet," which remains uninflected in the middle case, but in the masculine case has endings according to the pattern of "castle."
Civilization on borrowed time
Recently, I recalled a beautiful "order" from one of the great stories by Šimka and Grossmann, set partly in a cemetery, which reads as follows: "I warned her that she was crying all right, but at someone else's grave!" It occurred to me that many world politicians engaged in the senseless fight against climate change are now behaving in a very similar way.
They behave as if humans ruled the planet Earth. In reality, we are just a speck on its surface, which it can blow out with its enormous forces like a strong gust of wind blows out the flame of a candle. Probably, few of them watch the famous British and American natural science documentaries dealing with the destructive capabilities of our blue marble. After all, it would be enough for one of the larger active volcanoes to "blow up" and our advanced civilization would be ruined.
According to leading volcanologists, a number of large volcanoes are "locked and loaded" (for example, Katla in Iceland).
In a way, it would be ideal if the eruption, if it has to happen, happens as soon as possible, before wasting trillions of dollars on measures to reduce the production of carbon dioxide, because any really angry volcano can release it, along with dust and poisonous volcanic gases, at least a hundred times more than was saved at the expense of the people of Europe.
Forcibly limiting the production of CO2 therefore makes no sense. Moreover, it has been scientifically proven that with a significantly higher proportion of it in the air, plants produce more biological matter and are also more resistant to drought. For mankind, possible warming is significantly more favorable than, for example, a rapid return of the ice age.
If we take into account the still insufficiently studied influence of solar cycles on the Earth's climate, we can only come to one reasonable conclusion: Let's try hard to keep the Earth as clean as possible, and let's try to adapt to other changes with which we can't compete by force at the lowest possible cost!
