The car tuner brought the voice of the digital soul
Everything you know about obesity is wrong, declares the headline of a lengthy piece written for the Huffington Post by Michael Hobbes and photographed by Finlay Mackay. In a provocative afterword, it says that the medical community has ignored the facts about obesity for decades and waged a relentless (and also unnecessary) war against overweight people, which has not only affected public opinion, but also destroyed many lives. But now it's time for a new paradigm.
What Hobbes mentions at the outset is the fact that from knowledge and knowledge of the facts to putting into practice is often a very long and tiring journey. He mentions the case of scurvy, when some captains already in the seventeenth century handed out lemons, limes and oranges to their crew with the belief that they would prevent the disease. However, the British Navy abandoned this practice due to fears of increased costs. The clear influence of the fruit in the prevention and treatment of the disease was then demonstrated in the middle of the 18th century, but it took another fifty years for the Navy to take it into account. Seat belts also existed long before the invention of the car, but they became mandatory only in the sixties, as well as the first confirmed death in connection with asbestos dates back to 1906, although its first ban came in 1973.
"Every public health breakthrough - no matter how significant - has always had to compete with traditions, prejudices, and financial incentives within the society in which it was to be implemented," writes Hobbes. In American society today, nearly 80 percent of the adult population and about one-third of children meet the definition of overweight or obesity. More Americans now live with obesity than with breast cancer, Alzheimer's, Parkinson's, and HIV combined.
Obesity, on the other hand, is seen as a highly personal failure of the individual, which is said to burden health care and reduce GDP. The fear of fatness is so great in the population that Americans now spend more money on diets than they spend on computer games and films. But the truth is that diets do not work. As early as 1959, research showed that 95 to 98% of attempts to lose weight end in failure, and two-thirds of people on a diet subsequently gain more than they lost.
Armed with statistics, Hobbes goes on to describe the lifestyles and traumas of overweight people, where the personal meets the systemic, where, for example, in medical schools, the training of future doctors devotes only 19 hours of the entire course to the issue of nutrition, at a time when 60% of the calories consumed by Americans come from ultra-processed food.
Just how stigmatized obesity is is illustrated by reports from doctor's offices, where overweight people typically experience shorter office visits, are treated with less empathy by doctors and are seen as more problematic patients.
But being overweight is far from just an American problem, as Hobbes writes. Since 1980, the prevalence of obesity has doubled in 73 countries and increased in 113, and no country has managed to reduce or stop this increase.
