The library commemorates the anniversary of the death of Václav IV with an exhibition of manuscripts
Six rare historical manuscripts from the turn of the 14th and 15th centuries, i.e. from the time of the Roman and Czech King Wenceslas IV, can be viewed by people in Prague's Klementinum today and on Saturday. The National Library has released them from its vaults to commemorate this year's 600th anniversary of Wenceslas's death. This morning, librarians and restorers placed the rare originals in display cases in the Mirror Chapel. Admission to the exhibition is free, it is open both days from 10:00 to 18:00.
The exhibition of documents entitled Ad mandatum domini Regis: From the royal office and library of Václav IV was prepared by the library together with the National Archive. The National Archive looks at the written heritage from the reign of Václav IV from the perspective of official documents and the National Library from the perspective of literary works, said its author Jan Vojtíšek.
"Visitors can look forward, for example, to a work on agriculture by Petr de Crescentiis, which is essentially a kind of encyclopedia of agriculture, or to a breviary, i.e. a prayer book by one of the Benedictine nuns of the Monastery of St. George at Prague Castle, from the beginning of the 15th century," he listed the reasons why people should, in his opinion, visit the exhibition.
The Epistles of Peter of Blois will also be on display, where the introductory miniature H (enrico) depicts the half-length figure of the English king Henry II. The author of the decoration is most likely the Master of Samson's History, who, in addition to the two volumes of the Bible of Wenceslas IV, also participated in the decoration of a number of other manuscripts. Visitors will also see the Latin anthology of John Wycliffe's tracts from the period around 1411 to 1414.
Not a single book from the library of Wenceslas IV has been preserved on Czech territory. According to experts, this library belonged to the most extensive and also the most beautiful book collections in Central Europe at that time, because the young king longed to build a representative library that would match the book collections of his French relatives. However, the library ceased to exist soon after Wenceslas' death. Apparently, it was stolen or destroyed during the conquest of the castle by the Hussites. However, several codices were saved. Most of them are now owned by the Austrian National Library.
"We have a whole range of treasures in our collections and I am glad that they are in a condition that allows them to be exhibited and made available to the public so-called live and not only in the form of the digital library Manuscriptorium," said the Director of the National Library, Martin Kocanda.
On the day of Saturday's national holiday, an exhibition entitled What's Hiding Under the Floor, which presents local archaeological discoveries, will also be open free of charge in Klementinum.
