Museum in Semily returns to the Velvet Revolution with an exhibition
An imitation of a normalization room with a television showing footage of the brutal police intervention against students on 17 November 1989 in Prague. This is also in the new exhibition of the museum in Semily, which is dedicated to the Velvet Revolution. "The basis is to present what happened in Semily after the events on Národní třída," said the curator of the exhibition, Tomáš Chvátal.
"I would say that the atmosphere was basically the same everywhere, with the first demonstration taking place in Semily on 22 November, and then more people gradually arriving every day," he said. Among the most active at the beginning was a group of local dissidents around Miroslav Matěcha, who was the only one from the city and the immediate surroundings to sign Charter 77, and the Dědečková couple, who were circulating the petition "Several Sentences." According to Chvátal, the Civic Forum was also formed relatively quickly at that time. "One specificity is that there was a very strong group of local doctors in the Civic Forum," said the curator.
Visitors should be drawn into the events in the city at that time by around 50 photographs, the pictures were taken 30 years ago by Karel Bárta. A video from the general strike on 27 November 1989, shot by František Tomíček, has also been preserved and will be played on a loop for the entire duration of the exhibition. Ivan Hlas also spoke and sang at the demonstration. The Semily archive has also lent a number of preserved banners from that time for the exhibition. "They said: Let's not get drunk with a roll, From trough to trough, We don't want violence," said Chvátal. Some changes in the city were very rapid at the time, for example, in December, people decided in a city-wide vote that the square would be Riegrovo and cancelled the previous name Gottwaldovo.
The exhibition also captures the events before the November events. "In the first part, we present to witnesses and students what was before, such a late normalization. I think we managed to collect unique documents from Semily, whether they are banners with various communist slogans or a bronze plaque from the then museum of the workers' movement," said Chvátal. One room is supposed to evoke the feeling of what it might have looked like in the living room of an ordinary household.
The last part of the exhibition is dedicated to what happened after the Velvet Revolution. It is focused on the first free elections. "We wallpapered one room with election posters. Anyone who experienced it will recall the posters "With us to Europe" or there is Václav Klaus still under the heading of the OF with the beautiful motto "Every man for his community," added the curator.
