If the number of members of the tenant's household decreases, the tenant is obliged to notify the landlord without undue delay.
Obligations of the lessee:
- use the apartment properly in accordance with the lease agreement
- to observe, for the duration of the lease, the usual rules of behaviour in the house and the reasonable instructions of the landlord to maintain the proper order customary according to local conditions
- carry out and pay for routine maintenance and minor repairs related to the use of the apartment
- to tolerate the modification of the apartment or house, or its reconstruction or other change, only if it does not reduce the value of the housing and if it can be carried out without major inconvenience for the tenant, or if the landlord carries it out on the order of a public authority, or if there is a direct threat of particularly serious harm.
In other cases, the change can be made only with the consent of the lessee.
- if the lessee finds any damage or defect in the apartment that needs to be removed without delay, he will immediately notify the lessor; any other defect or damage that prevents normal living will be notified to the lessor without undue delay.
The lessee is obliged to do, according to his possibilities, what can be expected, so that the damage or defect, which must be removed without delay, does not cause further damage.
The lessee is entitled to reimbursement of costs reasonably incurred in preventing further damage, unless the damage or defect was caused by circumstances for which the lessee is responsible.
- if the tenant knows in advance that he will be absent from the apartment for more than two months and that the apartment will be difficult to access during this period, he is obliged to inform the landlord in time.
At the same time, he is obliged to notify a person who will ensure the possibility of entering the apartment during his absence in the event that this is absolutely necessary; if the tenant does not have such a person at hand, the landlord is such a person.
If the lessee fails to fulfil this obligation, this action is considered to be a serious breach of the lessee's obligations; this does not apply if no serious damage occurs for this reason.
- pay rent according to this contract
- carry out routine maintenance of the leased object
- notify the lessor that the item has a defect, which the lessor is obliged to remove, immediately after it is discovered, or when it could have been discovered through careful use of the item
- if a third party asserts a proprietary or other right to the thing, or if a third party requests the return or removal of the thing, the lessee is obliged to notify the lessor in writing; if he requests it, the lessor is obliged to provide him with protection.
If the landlord does not provide the tenant with sufficient protection, the tenant may terminate the lease without notice.
If the lessee is disturbed in the use of the thing or otherwise affected by the actions of a third party, he has the right to a reasonable rent discount if he has reported such actions of the third party to the lessor in a timely manner.
- if the lessor notifies this in advance within a reasonable time, the lessee will allow him to inspect the thing to the necessary extent, as well as access to it or to it, in order to carry out the necessary repair or maintenance of the thing.
Prior notification is not required if it is necessary to prevent damage or if there is a risk of delay.
If such activities of the landlord create difficulties for the tenant, which are not insignificant, the tenant has the right to a discount on the rent.
- insure the subject of the lease ...
VI. Sublease
The tenant may sublet part of the apartment to a third party only if he lives in the apartment himself.
The provisions of Section 2272 of the Civil Code shall apply mutatis mutandis.
In the event that the tenant does not live in the apartment permanently, he may sublet the apartment or its part to a third party only with the written consent of the landlord.
The request for consent must also be in writing.
If the lessor does not respond to this request within one month, the consent is deemed to have been given.
If the lessee violates the above-agreed obligations, it is considered that he has grossly violated his obligation.
The sublease ends together with the lease.
If the lease ends, the lessee is obliged to inform the sub-lessee in good time, stating the decisive facts, which are in particular the day of termination of the lease, the length of the notice period and the beginning of its run.
If the lessee allows a third party to use the thing in accordance with the law and this contract, he is responsible to the lessor for the actions of this person as if he used the thing himself.
VII. Termination of the lease
When handing over the item, the lessee is entitled to separate and take back everything that he has put into the item or brought to it at his own expense, if this is possible and if this does not worsen the nature of the item or if it does not make its use unreasonably difficult.
If the apartment is vacated during the lease period, the lease ends.
If part of the apartment is lost during the lease period, the lessee is entitled to either a reasonable discount on the rent or to terminate the lease without notice.
Termination of the lease requires a written form and must reach the other party.
The notice period runs from the first day of the calendar month following the receipt of the notice by the other party.
In the event of termination by the lessor, the lessor is obliged to inform the lessee of his right to object to the termination and to propose a review of the legitimacy of the termination by the court.
The landlord may terminate the lease within the three-month notice period only for the reasons specified in the provisions of Section 2288 of the Civil Code, and is obliged to state the reason for termination in the notice.
The tenant has the right to apply to the court to examine whether the notice is justified, within two months of the date on which the notice was received.
The landlord has the right to terminate the lease without notice in accordance with Section 2291 of the Civil Code.
and to require the lessee to hand over the apartment without undue delay, but no later than one month after the end of the lease, if the lessee breaches his obligation in a particularly serious manner, in particular:
