For their study, the scientists are looking for toddlers with a congenital defect known as valgus ankles.
Valgosity of the ankles is a congenital defect that affects five to ten percent of children. It is normally treated with intensive exercise. Scientists are trying to help these children even more, so they have developed special shoes that should significantly speed up the treatment.
"We have two prototypes of shoes that will be worn by healthy children and children with a diagnosis in order to map the effect in both groups. Participation in the research will not have any risks for the children and the measurement will be completely painless," explains Marta Gimunová, head of research from the Faculty of Sports Studies at MU.
Parents of both groups of children can register for the study via the website, where the registration form and all information is available.
The researchers are looking for 50 children with a diagnosis and 50 healthy children. Of each group, half will always wear medical shoes and half will not.
"The moment when parents should enrol their child is when they take their first independent steps, for example, when they typically let go of the furniture they are holding on to when trying to walk. Participation in the research involves three measurements over the course of seven months from the child's first steps, each of which takes about 20 minutes, and for half of the participants it also involves wearing the tested shoes," points out Gimunová.
