Comment by Jan Šindelář: Managing railways as a company
The heavenly election, even if it was not entirely smooth, is the culmination of a sad story of the inability of the state to give a clear direction to the roads. The board has been incomplete for over a year and even after Wednesday evening it does not change because one of the members resigned. The provisional period continues.
The selection process itself was a farce from the start, if only because the requirements for candidates, especially in the field of practical experience, were significantly eased. Compared to last year's selection, the requirements for the size of the company in which the candidate had worked in the past were reduced. First, the members of the selection committee and then the supervisory board only played the role of pimps.
Nebeský presented probably the weakest professional CV of the five finalists, yet without experience from a large company, he beat experienced players from the management of logistics giants and transport companies. It was the participation of interesting managers from the private sector that was probably the brightest side (and the greatest hope) of the whole process. Today, those concerned know that they only played the role of narrative backdrops in the political game.
Maybe Nebeský will surprise, show great talent and eventually prove to be the best head of railways of all time. At least in the beginning, however, he will be accompanied by the aftertaste of political smoke. Czech Railways does not expect an easy period, they have to cope with competition in the liberalization of the market and with a shortage of employees in operation. Train drivers, shunters and mechanics are missing. What kind of motivation for further work and respect for management should they have when the state behaves in top management like an elephant in a china shop?
The second important group is the creditors. We will see how they interpret the games at the head of the railways next spring, when the railways defend the rating. It is certain that the creditors perceive instability. It is sad that someone else goes to Moody's every year to defend the rating for České dráhy. The agency has not missed frequent changes in the management of the railways and political influence on the company, it criticized them already this summer.
The ANO movement promotes, among other things, the slogan that the state should be managed like a company. For starters, it would be enough if one large state-owned company was managed like a company and not like a state. Czech Railways is still one of the largest companies in the country and it would be good if it were managed by the best. They applied, but the state despised them. It can certainly be argued that the post at the head of the railways has always been a political matter. But then we can forgive ourselves the antics of the selection process.
