Microplastics have reached human intestines, study confirms for the first time
A team led by the professor of the University of Vienna, Philipp Schwabl, has published a study that for the first time proves the presence of microplastics in human faeces. Although the study is small, with eight participants from Europe, Japan and Russia - nevertheless, tiny plastic particles measuring between 50 and 500 micrometres were found in the samples of all examined persons. None of the eight subjects was a vegetarian, six of them did not avoid sea fish, they all drank water from plastic bottles and food packaged in plastic.
And it would actually be a bit of a miracle if nothing were found. We already know that microplastics - which are either produced directly, for example for the needs of the cosmetics industry, or are formed by the disintegration of larger pieces - are present in marine animals, insects, tap water and soft drinks; in short, everywhere on the planet. Their entry into the human digestive tract has therefore only been officially confirmed. There were approximately 20 microplastic particles per ten grams of stool, and scientists estimate that more than half of the world's population will have them in their bodies.
Of course, both lay and scientific awareness suspect that this is not good. However, mankind still does not know how bad it is - and what effect microplastics have on the "host" organisms. Small particles can get into the bloodstream or into the lymphatic system and end up in the liver, for example. "This is the first study of its kind and confirms what we have long thought. Now that we have the first evidence of the occurrence of microplastics in the human body, we must continue to investigate what exactly this means for human health," says Schwabl.
So far, it is known that microplastics in the intestines can negatively affect the immune reactions of the digestive system, thus facilitating the absorption of toxic chemicals and other pathogens into the body. And so far, there is no known solution other than to limit the use of plastics, especially polypropylene. However, this will be difficult - the first task facing governments and authorities will be to at least stop its steep increase. As far as plastic bottles are concerned, experts estimate that in three years humanity will consume a fifth more than today. The current rate is a staggering one million bottles purchased per minute. Every year, approximately eight million tons of plastic end up in the seas and oceans. Waste threatens marine ecosystems and contaminates the digestive systems of marine animals.
Some states have already introduced restrictions and other measures, Kenya, for example, has banned plastic bags - under the threat of draconian penalties. The European Commission is considering small bans (the well-known straws), and the domestic Ministry of the Environment is heading in the same direction. Critics, however, claim that such measures, although nice, are completely inadequate.
